1	\chapter{The Abel--Jacobi map}
2	\label{chap:AbelJacobi}
3	
4	Let $C$ be a smooth proper curve over $k$ as in Chapter~\ref{chap:Genus}, and let $\Jac(C)$ be its Jacobian (Definition~\ref{def:Jacobian}).
5	
6	\section{Definition}
7	
8	\begin{definition}\leanok
9	[Abel--Jacobi map]
10	  \label{def:ofCurve}
11	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.ofCurve}
12	  \uses{def:Jacobian}
13	  Given a $k$-rational point $P \colon \Spec k \to C$ --- equivalently, a morphism $P \colon \mathbf 1 \to C$ in the category of $k$-schemes --- the \emph{Abel--Jacobi map} is the $k$-morphism
14	  \[
15	    \alpha_P \colon C \;\longrightarrow\; \Jac(C),\qquad Q \;\longmapsto\; [\mathcal O_C(Q - P)].
16	  \]
17	  Functorially, it is the morphism in the category of $k$-schemes induced by the line bundle $\mathcal O_{C \times C}(\Delta - p_1^* P)$ on $C \times C$ via the universal property of $\Pic^0_{C/k}$.
18	\end{definition}
19	
20	\section{Pointed property}
21	
22	\begin{lemma}\leanok
23	[$\alpha_P$ sends $P$ to $0$]
24	  \label{lem:comp_ofCurve}
25	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.comp_ofCurve}
26	  \uses{def:ofCurve}
27	  $P \;\circ\; \alpha_P \;=\; \eta[\Jac(C)]$, where $\eta[\Jac(C)]$ is the identity element of the group scheme $\Jac(C)$.
28	\end{lemma}
29	
30	\begin{proof}
31	  \uses{def:ofCurve}
32	  \leanok
33	  At the level of $k$-points: $\alpha_P(P) = [\mathcal O_C(P - P)] = [\mathcal O_C] = 0$. Globally: by construction, $\alpha_P$ is the morphism classifying the line bundle $\mathcal O_{C \times C}(\Delta - p_1^* P)$; restricting to the section $(P, \mathrm{id})$ gives the trivial line bundle, hence the zero point of $\Pic^0$.
34	\end{proof}
35	
36	\section{Universal (Albanese) property}
37	
38	\begin{theorem}\leanok
39	[Albanese property of the Jacobian]
40	  \label{thm:exists_unique_ofCurve_comp}
41	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.exists_unique_ofCurve_comp}
42	  \uses{def:ofCurve, lem:comp_ofCurve}
43	  Let $A$ be an abelian variety over $k$ --- i.e.\ a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme over $k$. For every pointed morphism $f \colon C \to A$ with $f \circ P = \eta[A]$, there exists a unique group-scheme morphism $g \colon \Jac(C) \to A$ such that $f = g \circ \alpha_P$.
44	  \[
45	  \begin{array}{ccc}
46	    C & \stackrel{f}{\longrightarrow} & A \\
47	    {\scriptstyle\alpha_P} \downarrow & \nearrow {\scriptstyle\exists ! g} & \\
48	    \Jac(C) & &
49	  \end{array}
50	  \]
51	\end{theorem}
52	
53	\begin{proof}
54	  \uses{def:IsAlbanese, thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness, thm:IsAlbanese_unique}
55	  \leanok
56	  By Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}, there exists a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme $J$ over $k$ of dimension $g(C)$ such that, for every marked point $P \in C(k)$, the scheme $J$ together with a morphism $\iota_P \colon C \to J$ with $\iota_P \circ P = \eta_J$ satisfies the Albanese universal property of Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}. The Jacobian $\Jac(C)$ is defined as this scheme $J$, and the Abel--Jacobi map $\alpha_P$ of Definition~\ref{def:ofCurve} is the universal morphism $\iota_P$ associated with the chosen marked point $P$.
57	
58	  Existence and uniqueness of the factorisation $g$ are then exactly the universal-property data carried by $\iota_P$ in Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}: for every pointed $f \colon C \to A$ with $f \circ P = \eta_A$, there exists a unique $g \colon J \to A$ with $f = \iota_P \circ g$. Both the higher-genus content and the genus-$0$ rigidity (i.e.\ that every morphism from a genus-$0$ pointed curve to an abelian variety is constant) are absorbed into Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}.
59	\end{proof}
60	
61	\section{Implementation route via the Albanese framework}
62	
63	The three results above are formalised through the Albanese framework of Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian}. In the absence of Mathlib's Pic-scheme machinery, the Jacobian is defined as an Albanese object for every marked point (Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}); the universal-property data $(\iota_P, \text{factorisation})$ is then carried by the Albanese predicate (Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}) and projects directly into the three results of this chapter. Existence of a uniform-over-$P$ Albanese object is the single remaining mathematical hypothesis pending the formalisation of either Pic-scheme representability, symmetric-power quotients, or the rigidity theorem $\Hom(\mathbb P^1_k, A) = A(k)$ in Mathlib.
64	
65	The classical proof via line bundles --- using the universal property of $\Pic^0_{C/k}$, dual abelian varieties, and the rigidity theorem of Mumford \S4 --- gives the same conclusion but requires more Mathlib infrastructure. The Albanese-framework route used here is mathematically equivalent and bundles all of the missing infrastructure into the single hypothesis of Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}.
66

1	\chapter{Line bundles on schemes and the Picard group}
2	\label{chap:Picard_LineBundle}
3	
4	This chapter sets up the foundational Phase~B/C infrastructure: the type of \emph{line bundles} (invertible quasi-coherent sheaves) on a scheme $X$, the abelian-group structure under tensor product, and the pull-back functoriality. It is the smallest self-contained step toward the Picard scheme construction (Theorem~\ref{thm:Pic_representable}) and feeds the Jacobian gap chain.
5	
6	The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and lemma here is auxiliary, supporting the construction of $\Pic_{C/k}$ in later phases.
7	
8	\section{Definition}
9	
10	\begin{definition}\leanok
11	[Line bundle on a scheme]
12	  \label{def:Scheme_LineBundle}
13	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.LineBundle}
14	  Let $X$ be a scheme. A \emph{line bundle} on $X$ is an invertible quasi-coherent $\mathcal O_X$-module: a sheaf $L$ of $\mathcal O_X$-modules that is quasi-coherent and locally free of rank $1$. Equivalently: an object of the category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules that is invertible with respect to the tensor product $- \otimes_{\mathcal O_X} -$ in the symmetric monoidal category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules.
15	\end{definition}
16	
17	\paragraph{Status note (Phase C1).}
18	The Lean-side declaration referenced above currently uses a strictly weaker, global-sections approximation rather than the geometric definition stated here. Concretely, the body of \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.LineBundle} in \texttt{AlgebraicJacobian/Picard/LineBundle.lean} reads
19	\[
20	  \mathrm{LineBundle}\,X \;:=\; \mathrm{CommRing.Pic}\bigl(\Gamma(X, \top)\bigr),
21	\]
22	i.e.\ the Picard group of the commutative ring of global sections, rather than the group of invertible quasi-coherent $\mathcal O_X$-modules.
23	By Stacks~\texttt{0AGS}, this approximation coincides with the true Picard group $\Pic(X)$ when $X$ is affine, but is in general a \emph{strict} subgroup when $X$ is non-affine. A concrete witness: for $X = \mathbb P^n_k$ with $n \geq 1$, the true Picard group is $\Pic(\mathbb P^n_k) \cong \mathbb Z$, whereas the current Lean body computes $\mathrm{CommRing.Pic}(k)$, which is trivial.
24	
25	The dependent chapters acknowledge this mismatch and refuse to propagate the error downstream: see the forward-compatibility note in Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor} and the status remark on \texttt{W.IsMonoidal} in Chapter~\ref{chap:Modules_Monoidal}. In particular, the representability obligation (Theorem~\ref{thm:Pic_representable}) remains a \texttt{sorry} pending the geometric definition; no chapter weakens its statement to the approximation.
26	
27	The Phase~C1 refactor scheduled in \texttt{STRATEGY.md} will replace the Lean body of \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.LineBundle} by the geometric definition described above, i.e.\ \texttt{MonoidalCategory.Invertible} applied to \texttt{X.Modules} in the symmetric monoidal category of quasi-coherent $\mathcal O_X$-modules. After C1, the \texttt{\textbackslash leanok} markers on Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_Pic_commGroup} and Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback}---which presently certify closure against the approximation-level body---will need to be re-confirmed against the refactored statements.
28	
29	\begin{remark}
30	  Mathlib has the category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules and the quasi-coherence typeclass. The combination ``invertible quasi-coherent sheaf'' is not pre-packaged; it is the content of this definition.
31	\end{remark}
32	
33	\section{Group structure under tensor product}
34	
35	% NOTE: \leanok holds for the current approximation-level Lean body (CommRing.Pic of global sections); the Phase~C1 refactor will re-establish this against the geometric statement. See "Status note (Phase C1)" above.
36	\begin{theorem}\leanok
37	[Picard group of a scheme]
38	  \label{thm:Scheme_Pic_commGroup}
39	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.instCommGroupLineBundle}
40	  For every scheme $X$, the type of line bundles on $X$ (modulo isomorphism) carries a canonical commutative-group structure. The operation is tensor product over $\mathcal O_X$, the unit is the structure sheaf $\mathcal O_X$ itself, and the inverse of a line bundle $L$ is its $\mathcal O_X$-dual $L^\vee = \mathcal{H}om_{\mathcal O_X}(L, \mathcal O_X)$.
41	
42	  We denote this group by $\Pic(X)$ and call it the \emph{Picard group} of $X$.
43	\end{theorem}
44	
45	\begin{proof}
46	  \uses{def:Scheme_LineBundle}
47	  \leanok
48	  Tensor product of two invertible quasi-coherent sheaves is invertible quasi-coherent (locally on $X$ this reduces to the corresponding statement for invertible modules over commutative rings, which Mathlib has). The structure sheaf is the tensor unit. The dual sheaf is the inverse: $L \otimes_{\mathcal O_X} L^\vee \cong \mathcal O_X$ canonically. Commutativity and associativity descend from the symmetric monoidal structure on the category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules.
49	\end{proof}
50	
51	\section{Pull-back functoriality}
52	
53	% NOTE: \leanok holds for the current approximation-level Lean body (CommRing.Pic of global sections); the Phase~C1 refactor will re-establish this against the geometric statement. See "Status note (Phase C1)" above.
54	\begin{theorem}\leanok
55	[Pull-back of line bundles]
56	  \label{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback}
57	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Pic.pullback}
58	  Let $f \colon X \to Y$ be a morphism of schemes. Pull-back of $\mathcal O_Y$-modules along $f$ restricts to a group homomorphism
59	  \[
60	    f^* \colon \Pic(Y) \;\to\; \Pic(X),\qquad L \;\mapsto\; f^* L \;:=\; f^{-1} L \otimes_{f^{-1}\mathcal O_Y} \mathcal O_X.
61	  \]
62	  Pull-back preserves invertibility, commutes with tensor product, and is functorial: $(\mathrm{id}_X)^* = \mathrm{id}_{\Pic(X)}$ and $(f \circ g)^* = g^* \circ f^*$.
63	\end{theorem}
64	
65	\begin{proof}
66	  \uses{thm:Scheme_Pic_commGroup}
67	  \leanok
68	  Mathlib has the tensor product of $\mathcal O_X$-modules and the pullback of sheaves of modules along a scheme morphism. Pull-back commutes with tensor product. Functoriality is the standard sheaf-pullback functoriality.
69	\end{proof}
70	
71	\section{Use in the project}
72	
73	The Picard group $\Pic(X)$ is the underlying \emph{set} (modulo isomorphism) of the Picard \emph{scheme} $\Pic_{C/k}$ in the curve case; the scheme structure adds a $k$-scheme of finite type representing the relative Picard functor $S \mapsto \Pic(C \times_k S) / \Pic(S)$.
74	
75	This chapter is therefore the gateway to:
76	\begin{itemize}
77	  \item Definition~\ref{def:Pic_functor} (Picard functor of $C/k$) --- quotient by $\Pic(S)$ uses Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback}.
78	  \item Theorem~\ref{thm:Pic_representable} (representability of the Picard scheme) --- uses the full $\Pic$ machinery built here.
79	  \item Definition~\ref{def:ofCurve} (Abel--Jacobi map) --- defined via the line bundle $\mathcal O_{C \times C}(\Delta - p_1^* P)$ on $C \times C$, an explicit element of $\Pic(C \times C)$.
80	\end{itemize}
81	
82	\section{Mathlib gap}
83	
84	Mathlib has:
85	\begin{itemize}
86	  \item The abelian category of sheaves of $\mathcal O_X$-modules on a scheme $X$.
87	  \item Quasi-coherence as data on a sheaf of modules.
88	  \item Invertibility for modules over a commutative ring.
89	  \item The Picard group of a commutative ring.
90	\end{itemize}
91	
92	What is missing and supplied by this chapter:
93	\begin{itemize}
94	  \item A scheme-side type of \emph{invertible quasi-coherent} sheaves and the proof that this property is preserved by tensor product.
95	  \item A scheme-side commutative-group instance on the Picard group.
96	  \item A scheme-morphism-functorial pull-back homomorphism $\Pic(Y) \to \Pic(X)$.
97	\end{itemize}
98	
99	These are mapped to Phase~B/C step~1 of the project strategy.
100

1	\chapter{The relative Picard functor}
2	\label{chap:Picard_Functor}
3	
4	This chapter sets up Phase~C step~2: the \emph{relative Picard functor} of a curve $C$ over $\Spec k$, packaged as a contravariant functor on schemes, and the (deferred) representability theorem whose closure delivers the Picard scheme. It is the natural successor to Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}.
5	
6	The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and lemma here is auxiliary, supporting the construction of $\Jac(C)$ in Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian}.
7	
8	\section{Definition}
9	
10	\begin{definition}\leanok
11	[Relative Picard functor]
12	  \label{def:Pic_functor}
13	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctor}
14	  Let $C$ be a scheme over $\Spec k$. The \emph{relative Picard functor} of $C$ over $k$ is the contravariant functor
15	  \[
16	    \PicardFunctor\, C \;\colon\; \mathrm{Sch}_k^{\mathrm{op}} \;\longrightarrow\; \mathrm{Set},\qquad
17	    S \;\longmapsto\; \Pic(C \times_k S) \,\big/\, p_S^* \Pic(S),
18	  \]
19	  where $p_S \colon C \times_k S \to S$ is the projection and the quotient is by the subgroup $p_S^*\Pic(S) \subseteq \Pic(C \times_k S)$ pulled back from $S$. Functoriality in $S$ is via base change of the fiber product and the pull-back homomorphism on Picard groups (Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback}).
20	\end{definition}
21	
22	\begin{remark}
23	  The presheaf $\PicardFunctor$ above is sometimes called the \emph{absolute} Picard presheaf; the standard \emph{relative Picard functor} of $C/k$ is its \'etale-sheafification, denoted $\underline{\Pic}_{C/k}$. For a smooth proper geometrically connected curve $C$ over a field $k$, \'etale sheafification is automatic on schemes that are themselves Picard sheaves over $S$ (the obstruction is the Brauer group), so this chapter records the presheaf definition; the \'etale sheafification is deferred to a subsequent iteration (Phase~C step~3).
24	\end{remark}
25	
26	\section{Representability}
27	
28	\begin{theorem}\leanok
29	[Representability of the Picard functor --- Grothendieck FGA, Mumford \emph{Abelian Varieties} \S III.13]
30	  \label{thm:Pic_representable}
31	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctor.representable}
32	  \uses{def:Pic_functor}
33	  Let $C$ be a smooth proper geometrically irreducible curve over a field $k$. Then $\PicardFunctor\, C$ (after \'etale sheafification) is representable by a smooth, locally finite-type group scheme $\Pic_{C/k}$ over $k$. Its connected component of the identity $\Pic^0_{C/k}$ is a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme over $k$ of dimension $g = g(C)$, hence an abelian variety.
34	\end{theorem}
35	
36	\begin{proof}
37	  \uses{def:Pic_functor, def:Scheme_LineBundle, thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback, thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}
38	  See \emph{Fundamental Algebraic Geometry: Grothendieck's FGA Explained} (Fantechi--G\"ottsche--Illusie--Kleiman--Nitsure--Vistoli, 2005), Chapter~9, and Mumford, \emph{Abelian Varieties}, Chapter~III \S13. The classical proof goes via Hilbert schemes and quotient stacks. Mathlib does not yet have the surrounding infrastructure (Hilbert schemes, quotients of schemes by finite group actions, FGA representability for moduli functors), so closing this theorem is a multi-iteration Mathlib-gap-fill task. The path adopted in this project (re-opened in iteration~076) decomposes the work into four steps (see \texttt{STRATEGY.md} Phase~C):
39	  \begin{enumerate}
40	    \item \emph{Step~C0} --- supply the symmetric monoidal structure on $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ (Chapter~\ref{chap:Modules_Monoidal}, Theorem~\ref{thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}).
41	    \item \emph{Step~C1} --- refine $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$ (Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}) from the global-sections approximation to ``invertible $\mathcal O_X$-module''.
42	    \item \emph{Step~C2} --- re-derive $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}$, $\PicardFunctor$, and the \'etale sheafification against the refined $\mathrm{LineBundle}$.
43	    \item \emph{Step~C3} --- construct $\Pic_{C/k}$ (representing scheme) and identify its identity component $\Pic^0_{C/k}$ with $\Jac(C)$. Two routes are viable: (a) the FGA route via a Hilbert/Quot detour (Mathlib-PR-sized); (b) the symmetric-power route via $\mathrm{Sym}^g C$, requiring a project-local quotient-by-finite-group construction. The route is chosen during step~C2.
44	  \end{enumerate}
45	  Until steps~C0--C3 are complete, the Lean-side sorry remains; downstream consumers (Definition~\ref{def:Jacobian} and the four Jacobian instances of Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian}) record their dependence on it through the bundled hypothesis \texttt{nonempty\_jacobianWitness}.
46	\end{proof}
47	
48	\section{Use in the project}
49	
50	Theorem~\ref{thm:Pic_representable} is the bundled blocker for the four Jacobian.lean sorries:
51	
52	\begin{itemize}
53	  \item Definition~\ref{def:Jacobian} ($\Jac(C) = \Pic^0_{C/k}$) takes the connected component of identity of the representing scheme.
54	  \item Theorem~\ref{thm:Jacobian_grpObj} (group-object structure) is the abelian-variety structure on $\Pic^0_{C/k}$.
55	  \item Theorem~\ref{thm:Jacobian_smooth_genus} (smooth of relative dimension $g$) is the dimension formula in the representability statement.
56	  \item Theorem~\ref{thm:Jacobian_proper} (properness) and Theorem~\ref{thm:Jacobian_geomIrred} (geometric irreducibility) are direct consequences of the representability conclusion.
57	\end{itemize}
58	
59	\section{Mathlib gap}
60	
61	Mathlib has the constituent infrastructure for the \emph{definition} (Definition~\ref{def:Pic_functor}):
62	\begin{itemize}
63	  \item Fiber products of schemes.
64	  \item Line bundles and Picard groups (this project, Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}).
65	  \item Pull-back of line bundles (this project, Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}).
66	  \item Quotient groups for group quotients.
67	  \item Functor machinery for assembling the contravariant functor.
68	\end{itemize}
69	
70	What is \emph{missing} and supplied by this chapter (as a deferred sorry):
71	\begin{itemize}
72	  \item The actual representability theorem (Theorem~\ref{thm:Pic_representable}). FGA-level, kept as a sorry; all four Jacobian.lean sorries reduce to it once it is closed.
73	\end{itemize}
74	
75	\subsection{Forward-compatibility note (LineBundle approximation)}
76	
77	Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle} defines line bundles via a global-sections approximation, correct on affine schemes but a strict subgroup of the true $\Pic(X)$ on non-affine schemes. The \emph{definition} of $\PicardFunctor C$ therefore inherits this approximation: the values $\PicardFunctor(S)$ for non-affine $S$ are smaller subgroups of the true relative Picard group. Consequently the representability theorem stated above will be honest only after the line bundle definition is refined to the bespoke ``invertible quasi-coherent sheaf'' definition (gated on monoidal-category infrastructure for $\mathcal O_X$-modules, currently absent). Until that refinement lands, the representable sorry of this chapter must remain unattacked: closing it on the approximate definition would silently assert representability of the wrong functor.
78

1	\chapter{The relative Picard functor as an abelian-group-valued presheaf}
2	\label{chap:Picard_FunctorAb}
3	
4	This chapter is the natural successor to Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}. The relative Picard functor of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor} is set-valued; the construction merely forgets the abelian-group structure that the values $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$ carry by definition. To set up Phase~C step~3 (\'etale sheafification) and any future cohomology-of-Picard-presheaf work, we need an abelian-group-valued variant whose values agree on the nose with the set-valued ones.
5	
6	The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and lemma here is auxiliary, supporting Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian} via the same path as Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}.
7	
8	\section{Definition}
9	
10	\begin{definition}\leanok
11	[Relative Picard functor, abelian-group valued]
12	  \label{def:Pic_functorAb}
13	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb}
14	  \uses{def:Pic_functor}
15	  Let $C$ be a scheme over $\Spec k$. The \emph{abelian-group-valued relative Picard functor} of $C$ over $k$ is the contravariant functor
16	  \[
17	    \PicardFunctorAb\, C \;\colon\; (\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}} \;\longrightarrow\; \AddCommGrpCat,\qquad
18	    S \;\longmapsto\; \mathtt{AddCommGrpCat.of}\;\bigl(\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)\bigr),
19	  \]
20	  with morphisms induced by the quotient pull-back maps defined in Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}.
21	\end{definition}
22	
23	\begin{remark}
24	  The underlying-set functor of $\PicardFunctorAb\, C$ agrees on the nose with the set-valued Picard functor of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}: Definition~\ref{def:Pic_functor} computes the same group quotient $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$ but discards the group structure. The forget-and-recover natural iso (Definition~\ref{def:PicardFunctorAb_forgetCompare} below) records this. It is needed to transport later results (e.g.\ representability) between the two flavours.
25	\end{remark}
26	
27	\section{Forget-and-recover natural iso}
28	
29	\begin{definition}\leanok
30	[$\PicardFunctorAb$ recovers $\PicardFunctor$ along forget]
31	  \label{def:PicardFunctorAb_forgetCompare}
32	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb.forgetCompare}
33	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb, def:Pic_functor}
34	  Let $C$ be a scheme over $\Spec k$. Then there is a natural isomorphism of set-valued functors
35	  \[
36	    \PicardFunctorAb\, C \,\circ\, \forget \AddCommGrpCat \;\cong\; \PicardFunctor\, C
37	  \]
38	  in $(\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}} \to \mathrm{Set}$.
39	\end{definition}
40	
41	\begin{proof}
42	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb, def:Pic_functor}
43	  \leanok
44	  Both sides have the same object at $S \in (\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}}$ --- the quotient set $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$ --- and the same map on morphisms --- the quotient pull-back. The additive wrapper is type-equal to its underlying multiplicative quotient, so the two functors agree on the nose at the underlying-type level. The natural iso is therefore the identity natural transformation in disguise.
45	\end{proof}
46	
47	\begin{lemma}\leanok
48	[Forget-evaluation simp lemma]
49	  \label{lem:PicardFunctorAb_forget_obj}
50	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb_forget_obj}
51	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb, def:PicardFunctorAb_forgetCompare}
52	  For every $S \in (\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}}$,
53	  \[
54	    (\forget\,\AddCommGrpCat).\mathrm{obj}\,\bigl((\PicardFunctorAb\, C).\mathrm{obj}\,S\bigr) \;=\; (\PicardFunctor\, C).\mathrm{obj}\,S.
55	  \]
56	\end{lemma}
57	
58	\begin{proof}
59	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb, def:PicardFunctorAb_forgetCompare}
60	  \leanok
61	  Definitionally true: both sides are the underlying carrier of the quotient $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$.
62	\end{proof}
63	
64	\section{\'Etale sheafification}
65	
66	The \'etale-sheafified relative Picard functor is built on top of $\PicardFunctorAb$. The Mathlib gap that previously blocked this (sheafification for the \'etale topology over $\Spec k$ valued in $\AddCommGrpCat$) closed in current Mathlib. The only remaining gymnastic is universe-pinning: the inferable sheafification is at value-universe $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u+1\}$, while $\PicardFunctorAb$ lands at $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u\}$; we bridge the gap by post-composing with the universe lift.
67	
68	\begin{definition}\leanok
69	[\'Etale-sheafified relative Picard functor]
70	  \label{def:PicardFunctorAb_etaleSheafified}
71	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb.etaleSheafified}
72	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb}
73	  Let $C$ be a scheme over $\Spec k$. The \emph{\'etale-sheafified relative Picard functor} of $C$ over $k$ is the \'etale sheaf on $\Sch_k$ obtained by sheafifying $\PicardFunctorAb\, C$ post-composed with the natural universe lift $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u\} \to \AddCommGrpCat.\{u+1\}$.
74	\end{definition}
75	
76	\begin{proof}
77	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb}
78	  \leanok
