201	\section{The $H^0$ algebraic bridge}
202	\label{sec:HModule_zero}
203	
204	After Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule} the cohomology groups $H^n_{\Module}(F)$ are well-defined and carry the canonical $k$-module structure. The next algebraic preliminary is the identification of the degree-zero piece $H^0_{\Module}(F)$ with a $\Hom$ group: the bridge from sheaf cohomology to representable Hom-functors.
205	
206	\begin{definition}\leanok
207	[$H^0$ as a $k$-linear Hom group]
208	  \label{def:Scheme_HModule_zero_linearEquiv}
209	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule_zero_linearEquiv}
210	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule, thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK, thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}
211	  Let $k$ be a field, $C$ a Grothendieck site admitting sheafification of $k$-modules and $\Ext$, and $F$ a sheaf of $k$-modules. Then there is a canonical $k$-linear equivalence
212	  \[
213	    H^0_{\Module}(F) \;\simeq_k\; \Hom(\text{constant sheaf at }k,\; F).
214	  \]
215	\end{definition}
216	
217	\begin{proof}
218	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule}
219	  \leanok
220	  Direct from Mathlib's $H^0$ bridge in any $k$-linear abelian category, applied to the sheaf category of $k$-modules. The $k$-linear enrichment is auto-inferable from the sheafification hypothesis.
221	\end{proof}
